creator: Various
description:
LibriVox recording of Short Poetry Collection 150 by Various.
Read in English by Leonard Wilson; Shakira Searle; Winston Tharp; Bruce Kachuk; Phil Schempf; Tony Addison; Isaiah Barker; Newgatenovelist; Son of the Exiles; John Burlinson; Becca Maggie
This is a collection of 24 poems read by LibriVox volunteers for November 2015. It includes: America for Me, by Henry van Dyke, read by Leonard Wilson An Argument, by Thomas Moore, read by Shakira Searle As imperceptibly as Grief, by Emily Dickinson, read by Winston Tharp At Sea, by James Whitcomb Riley, read by Bruce Kachuk The Ballad of the Black Fox Skin, by Robert W. Service, read by Phil Schempf The Burning Babe, by Robert Southwell, read by Tony Addison Discovered, by Paul Laurence Dunbar, read by Isaiah Barker Iris, by Michael Field, read by Newgatenovelist Keep Going, by Edgar A. Guest, read by Leonard Wilson The Light on the Wreck, by Henry Lawson, read by Son of the Exiles A Man Of Many Parts, by James Whitcomb Riley, read by Bruce Kachuk The Mental Traveller, by William Blake, read by Tony Addison Never give all the heart, by William Butler Yeats, read by Winston Tharp NO!, by Thomas Hood, read by Shakira Searle November, by Sara Teasdale, read by Shakira Searle Private Theatricals, by James Whitcomb Riley, read by Bruce Kachuk The Snows They Melt The Soonest, by Thomas Doubleday, read by Winston Tharp The Southerly Buster, by Henry Lawson, read by Son of the Exiles Thanksgiving, by Edgar A. Guest, read by Leonard Wilson The Teak Forest, by Laurence Hope, read by Newgatenovelist A Tom O' Bedlam Song, by Anonymous, read by Tony Addison The Two Songs, by William Blake, read by John Burlinson Up-Hill, by Christina Rossetti, read by Becca Maggie The Wizard's Funeral, by Richard Watson Dixon, read by Newgatenovelist For further information, including links to online text, reader information, RSS feeds, CD cover or other formats (if available), please go to the LibriVox catalog page for this recording.

For more free audio books or to become a volunteer reader, visit LibriVox.org.
